So, hm, how would someone (us, too) extend this to process more record types? It doesn't seem like one would be able to without rewriting all of `process`. Maybe, `process` could iterate over some registration of record types that are mapped to their respective methods. Something like (I have no idea if this would work, and this is just the first approach I thought of, there may be better ones):

```python
# original
class GCEEnricher:
    RECORD_HANDLERS = {
        'A': '_create_A_rrecord',  # string name of method
    }
    async def process(self, msg):
        # prep stuff
        for rtype, method in RECORD_HANDLERS.items():
            records = await getattr(self, method)(data, msg_logger)
        # other stuff

# extended
class MyEnricher(GCEEnricher):
    RECORD_HANDLERS.update({ 
        'CNAME': '_create_cname_rrecord',
    }
```

@scottpurdy, concerning
> Don't we have to add additional arguments if we want xml results or coverage written to a file?

Not anymore. In an earlier PR, you asked me to set global parameters for nupic.core to generate coverage html report and junit test results xml by default. See https://github.com/numenta/nupic.core/blob/master/setup.cfg.

The advantage of adding this to metadata is that the render portion of get_params_snippet() has no name specific code. Right now it is three lines:
``` python
for x in params_to_use:
    snippets.append(x[name_to_use])
return ', '.join(snippets)
```

If this isn't added to metadata, then there would need to be something like this:
``` python
for x in params_to_use:
    if name_to_use == 'python_name_with_default':
        <do the concatenation here>
    else:
        snippets.append(x[name_to_use])
return ', '.join(snippets)
```
This would make that function even longer, which I was trying to avoid.

This is the wording suggested here https://github.com/Azure/azure-cli/pull/5635#discussion_r171023298.

